# Internationalization (i18n) Implementation Rules

## Overview

All user-facing text in the application must be properly internationalized to support multiple languages (English, Russian).

## Translation Key Naming Convention

- Translation keys MUST use colon (`:`) as separator between namespace and key
- Format: `screenName:keyName` or `componentName:keyName`
- Examples: `ownerBookingScreen:title`, `loginScreen:emailLabel`, `common:cancel`
- Keys should be descriptive and self-explanatory

## Language Support

- ALWAYS translate for all two languages:
  - English (`en.ts`)
  - Russian (`ru.ts`)
- Add translations in the same commit as the feature implementation
- Keep translation structure consistent across all language files

## Using Translation Properties (tx)

- ALWAYS use native `tx` (or `txOptions`) props when available on components
- DO NOT use `translate()` function if component supports `tx` prop
- Common components with `tx` support:
  - `<Button tx="..." />` - instead of `text="..."`
  - `<Text tx="..." />` - instead of children
  - `<Header titleTx="..." />` - instead of `title="..."`
  - `<TextField placeholderTx="..." labelTx="..." helperTx="..." />` - instead of `placeholder`, `label`, `helper`

## Good vs Bad Examples

### âťŚ BAD - Using translate() function when tx prop is available

```tsx
import { translate } from "@/i18n/translate"

<Button text={translate("common:cancel")} onPress={handleCancel} />
<Text>{translate("loginScreen:title")}</Text>
<Header title={translate("profileScreen:title")} />
```

### âś… GOOD - Using tx props directly

```tsx
// No need to import translate function
<Button tx="common:cancel" onPress={handleCancel} />
<Text tx="loginScreen:title" />
<Header titleTx="profileScreen:title" />
```

### âś… ACCEPTABLE - Using translate() for dynamic content or logic

```tsx
import { translate } from "@/i18n/translate";

// When you need the translated string in logic
const errorMessage = translate("errors:invalidEmail");
Alert.alert(translate("common:error"), errorMessage);

// When building dynamic strings
const dateText = `${formatDate(date)} - ${translate("common:today")}`;
```

## Translation File Structure

- First look for translation in common section. If translation is really comon (simple 1-word - then should put it in common)
- Organize translations by screen or component or feature
- Each screen/component/feature should have its own namespace
- Common translations go in `common` namespace
- Type safety is enforced through TypeScript

Example structure in `en.ts`:

```typescript
const en = {
  common: {
    ok: "OK",
    cancel: "Cancel",
    back: "Back",
  },
  loginScreen: {
    title: "Let's get started",
    emailLabel: "Email address",
    passwordLabel: "Password",
  },
  ownerBookingComponent: {
    title: "Owner Booking",
    nextButton: "Next",
    confirmButton: "Confirm booking",
  },
};
```

## What NOT to Translate

- DO NOT translate:
  - Error messages from API responses
  - Technical error codes
  - Log messages
  - Debug information
  - Variable names or code
  - Configuration values

## Interpolation

- Use `{{variable}}` syntax for interpolation in translation strings
- Pass values using `txOptions` prop:

```tsx
// In translation file
withdrawFundsScreen: {
  amountExceedsError: "Amount cannot exceed {{amount}}";
}

// In component
<Text
  tx="withdrawFundsScreen:amountExceedsError"
  txOptions={{ amount: maxAmount }}
/>;
```

## Pluralization

- Use standard i18next pluralization rules
- Keys should include `_one`, `_other`, etc. suffixes where needed

## Checklist for Adding New Translations

1. âś… Add translation keys to all two language files (en, ru)
2. âś… Use `tx` props instead of `translate()` function when available
3. âś… Follow the `namespace:key` naming convention with colons
4. âś… Ensure translations are contextually appropriate for each language
5. âś… Run linter and fix any issues
6. âś… Test with different language settings if possible

## Testing Translations

- Verify translations appear correctly in all supported languages
- Check for missing translation keys (will display key instead of text)
- Ensure proper text wrapping and UI layout with longer translations (especially Russian)
- Test RTL support if applicable

## Import Guidelines

- Import `translate` function ONLY when needed for logic: `import { translate } from "@/i18n/translate"`
- Import type for type safety: `import type { TxKeyPath } from "@/i18n"`
- Do NOT import translate function if only using `tx` props on components

